[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837797326868&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837797326868&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

&gt; The following recored was recently added to, for a very short time, 
&gt; the top level utexas.edu zone so that decnet traffic could be 
&gt; forwarded to a standard host:
&gt;
&gt; *.decnet	in	mx 1	nic.the.net.
&gt;
&gt; What I would like to know is this a reasonable thing to do?

	My sense of purity probably would have required me to do this in
the mail system instead of the domain name system, but it's perfectly
legal.  One of the nice things about the domain name system is that you
can do almost anything you want within your own domain.  If it does what
you want (and doesn't offend your sense of purity ;-), go for it!

Note, however, that the very similar:

 *.decnet.	in	mx 1	nic.the.net.

would be illegal, because it makes "decnet" a top-level domain instead
of a sub-domain of utexas.edu.  That would probably get some people
rather annoyed at you.
						Philip

